lnotify is simple library binding libnotify to Lua, quite easy to use, supporting emergency levels. Pop up notifications from Lua to your desktop now is a piece of cake. 

To compile lnotify, you need o have installed the develpment files of libnotify and gtk+-2.0 . After that, just type "make" to compile:

$ make
gcc -O3 -Wall -Wmissing-prototypes -Wmissing-declarations -ansi -pedantic -fPIC -I/usr/include/lua5.1  `pkg-config --cflags --libs gtk+-2.0 libnotify`    -c -o notify.o notify.c
gcc -O3 -Wall -Wmissing-prototypes -Wmissing-declarations -ansi -pedantic -fPIC -I/usr/include/lua5.1  `pkg-config --cflags --libs gtk+-2.0 libnotify`  -o notify.so -shared  notify.o
$


To use lnotify is easy, just require it on Lua, like this:

$ lua
Lua 5.1.4  Copyright (C) 1994-2008 Lua.org, PUC-Rio
> require("notify")
> notify.message("This is my first test", "It works")
> notify.message("This is my first test", "It also works with icons", "/usr/share/icons/gnome/22x22/apps/calc.png") -- with icon


Look at test/ folder to see an example using emergency levels, icons, etc..

To install lnotify, just copy notify.so to your Lua library path, usually /usr/local/lib/lua/5.1/ , like:

$ sudo cp notify.so /usr/local/lib/lua/5.1/


Now, you can call lnotify from any Lua script, enjoy!



